# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acanthocephala
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephaliasis] It is acquired through consuming raw beetles or cockroaches, including the insect's larvae.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephaliasis] The parasite is widely distributed, but cases tend to occur where insects are eaten commonly.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephaliasis] Once ingested by a human, the worms will find their way to the intestine and mature.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephaliasis] There are severe symptoms due to the mechanical disruption of the lumen.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephaliasis] Acanthocephaliasis can be diagnosed by the presence of eggs in the stool.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephaliasis] There is no standardized treatment, but there has been some success with pyrantel pamoate, levamisole, niclosamide, mebendazole, ivermectin, paracetamol, tiabendazole, and piperazine citrate.
[src:acanthocephala/acanthocephaliasis] It is an uncommon condition, and literature on the topic in the field is sparse.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:acanthocephala/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The **acorn worms** or **Enteropneusta** are a hemichordate class of invertebrates.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The closest non-hemichordate relatives of the Enteropneusta are the echinoderms.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] There are 111 known species of acorn worm in the world, the main species for research being *Saccoglossus kowalevskii*.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Two families—Harrimaniidae and Ptychoderidae—separated at least 370 million years ago.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Until recently, it was thought that all species lived in the sediment on the seabed, subsisting as deposit feeders or suspension feeders.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] However, the early 21st century has seen the description of a new family, the Torquaratoridae, evidently limited to the deep sea, in which most of the species crawl on the surface of the ocean bottom and alternatively rise into the water column, evidently to drift to new foraging sites.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] It is assumed that the ancestors of acorn worms used to live in tubes like their relatives Pterobranchia, but that they eventually started to live a safer and more sheltered existence in sediment burrows instead.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The body length normally range from 2 centimetres (0.79 in) to 2.5 metres (8 ft 2 in) (*Balanoglossus gigas*), but one species, *Meioglossus psammophilus*, only reach 0.6 millimetres (0.024 in).
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Due to secretions containing elements like iodine, the animals have an iodoform-like smell.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Most acorn worms range from 9 to 45 centimetres (3.5 to 17.7 in) in length, with the largest species, *Balanoglossus gigas*, reaching 1.5 metres (5 ft) or more.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The body is made up of three main parts: an acorn-shaped proboscis, a short fleshy collar that lies behind it, and a long, worm-like trunk.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The creature's mouth is located at the collar behind the proboscis.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The skin is covered with cilia as well as glands that secrete mucus.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Some produce a bromide compound that gives them a medicinal smell and might protect them from bacteria and predators.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Acorn worms move only sluggishly, using ciliary action and peristalsis of the proboscis.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Many acorn worms are detritus feeders, eating sand or mud and extracting organic detritus.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Others feed on organic material suspended in the water, which they can draw into the mouth using the cilia on the gill bars.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Research indicates that the rate of feeding of acorn worms that are detritus feeders is dependent on food availability and flow rate.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] A groove lined with cilia lies just in front of the mouth and directs suspended food into the mouth and may allow the animal to taste.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The mouth cavity is tubular, with a narrow diverticulum or stomochord extending up into the proboscis.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] This diverticulum was once thought to be homologous with the notochord of chordates, hence the name "hemichordate" for the phylum.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The mouth opens posteriorly into a pharynx with a row of gill slits along either side.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The remainder of the digestive system consists of an oesophagus and intestine; there is no stomach.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] In some families there are openings in the dorsal surface of the oesophagus connecting to the external surface, through which water from the food can be squeezed, helping to concentrate it.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Digestion occurs in the intestine, with food material being pulled through by cilia, rather than by muscular action.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Acorn worms breathe by drawing in oxygenated water through their mouth.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The water then flows out the animal's gills which are on its trunk.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Thus, the acorn worm breathes about the same way as fish.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have an open circulatory system, in which the blood flows through the tissues sinuses.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] A dorsal blood vessel in the mesentery above the gut delivers blood to a sinus in the proboscis that contains a muscular sac acting as a heart.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Unlike the hearts of most other animals, however, this structure is a closed fluid-filled vesicle whose interior does not connect directly to the blood system.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Nonetheless, it does regularly pulsate, helping to push blood through the surrounding sinuses.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] From the central sinus in the collar, blood flows to a complex series of sinuses and peritoneal folds in the proboscis.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] This set of structures is referred to as a *glomerulus* and may have an excretory function, since acorn worms otherwise have no defined excretory system.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] From the proboscis, blood flows into a single blood vessel running underneath the digestive tract, from which smaller sinuses supply blood to the trunk, and back into the dorsal vessel.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The blood of acorn worms is colourless and acellular.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Acorn worms continually form new gill slits as they grow in size, with some older individuals of species like *Balanoglossus aurantiacus* having more than a hundred on each side.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The microscopic species *Meioglossus psammophilus* has just a single gill slit.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The gills in some acorn worms have cartilaginous support structures.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Each slit consists of a branchial chamber opening to the pharynx through a U-shaped cleft and to the exterior through a dorso-lateral pore (see diagram below).
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Cilia push water through the slits, maintaining a constant flow.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The tissues surrounding the slits are well supplied with blood sinuses.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] A plexus of nerves lies underneath the skin, and is concentrated into both dorsal and ventral nerve cords.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] While the ventral cord runs only as far as the collar, the dorsal cord reaches into the proboscis, and is partially separated from the epidermis in that region.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] This part of the dorsal nerve cord is often hollow, and may well be homologous with the brain of vertebrates.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] In acorn worms, it seems to be primarily involved with coordinating muscular action of the body during burrowing and crawling.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have no eyes, ears or other special sense organs, except for the ciliary organ in front of the mouth, which appears to be involved in filter feeding and perhaps taste.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] There are, however, numerous nerve endings throughout the skin.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have a Y-shaped nuchal skeleton that starts their proboscis and collar on their ventral side.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The length of the horns of the nuchal skeleton varies between species.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have a circulatory system with a heart that also functions as a kidney.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have gill-like structures that they use for breathing, similar to the gills of primitive fish.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Therefore, acorn worms are sometimes said to be a link between classical invertebrates and vertebrates.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Some also have a postanal tail which may be homologous to the post-anal tail of vertebrates.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] An interesting trait is that its three-section body plan is no longer present in the vertebrates, except for the anatomy of the frontal neural tube, later developed into a brain which is divided into three main parts.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] This means some of the original anatomy of the early chordate ancestors is still present even if it is not always visible.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] One theory is that the three-part body originates from an early common ancestor of all the deuterostomes, and maybe even from a common bilateral ancestor of both the deuterostomes and protostomes.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Studies have shown that the gene expression in the embryo share three of the same signaling centers that shape the brains of all vertebrates, but instead of taking part in the formation of their neural system, they are controlling the development of the different body regions.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The internal relationships within the Enteropneusta are shown below.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The tree is based on 16S +18S rRNA sequence data and phylogenomic studies from multiple sources, with the families Harrimaniidae and Ptychoderidae recovered as non-monophyletic.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Acorn worms are rarely seen by humans because of their lifestyle.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] They live in U-shaped burrows on the sea-bed, from the shoreline down to a depth of 10,000 ft.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The worms lie there with the proboscis sticking out of one opening in the burrow.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Acorn worms are generally slow burrowers.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] To obtain food, many acorn worms swallow sand or mud that contains organic matter and microorganisms in the manner of earthworms (this is known as deposit feeding).
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] At low tide, they stick out their rear ends at the surface and excrete coils of processed sediments (casts).
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Another method that some acorn worms use to obtain food is to collect suspended particles of organic matter and microbes from the water.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Acorn worms are dioecious, having separate biological sexes, although at least some species are also capable of asexual reproduction in the form of fragmentation.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] They have paired gonads, which lie close to the pharynx and release the gametes through a small pore near to the gill slits.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The female lays a large number of eggs embedded in a gelatinous mass of mucus, which are then externally fertilized by the male before water currents break up the mass and disperse the individual eggs.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] In most species, the eggs hatch into planktonic larvae with elongated bodies covered in cilia.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] In some species, these develop directly into adults, but in others, there is a free-swimming intermediate stage referred to as a *tornaria* larva.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] These are very similar in appearance to the bipinnaria larvae of starfishes, with convoluted bands of cilia running around the body.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] Since the embryonic development of the blastula within the egg is also very similar to that of echinoderms, this suggests a close phylogenetic link between the two groups.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] After a number of days or weeks, a groove begins to form around the larval midsection, with the anterior portion eventually destined to become the proboscis, while the remainder forms the collar and trunk.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] The larvae eventually settle down and change into tiny adults to take on the burrowing lifestyle.
[src:acanthocephala/acorn-worm] A few species, such as *Saccoglossus kowalevskii*, lack even the planktonic larval stage, hatching directly as miniature adults.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:acanthocephala/actinomycetota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:acanthocephala/aerophobota] The classification is based on genomic and metagenomic data without cultured isolates, and the name is not yet validly published under formal bacterial nomenclature.
[src:acanthocephala/aerophobota] Aerophobetes are abundant in hydrate-containing, silty sediment layers beneath the ocean floor and thrive in anoxic (oxygen-free) conditions.
[src:acanthocephala/aerophobota] Genetic analyses suggest they ferment organic matter, producing hydrogen and acetate, which can then be used by syntrophic methanogenic archaea to generate methane.
[src:acanthocephala/aerophobota] These metabolic interactions indicate Aerophobota's likely contribution to methane formation and carbon cycling in deep-sea ecosystems.
[src:acanthocephala/aerophobota] Research into Aerophobota and its functional roles is of interest because methane is a potent greenhouse gas.
[src:acanthocephala/aerophobota] Understanding these microbes could inform strategies for mitigating methane emissions from seafloor hydrates.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The **gastrointestinal tract** (also called the **GI tract**, **digestive tract**, and the **alimentary canal**) is the tract or passageway of the digestive system that leads from the mouth to the anus.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The tract is one of the largest of the body's systems.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The GI tract contains all the major organs of the digestive system, in humans and other animals, including the esophagus, stomach, and intestines.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Food taken in through the mouth is digested to extract nutrients and absorb energy, and the waste expelled at the anus as feces.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] *Gastrointestinal* is an adjective meaning of or pertaining to the stomach and intestines.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Most animals have a "through-gut" or complete digestive tract.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Exceptions are more primitive ones: sponges have small pores (ostia) throughout their body for digestion and a larger dorsal pore (osculum) for excretion, comb jellies have both a ventral mouth and dorsal anal pores, while cnidarians and acoels have a single pore for both digestion and excretion.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The human gastrointestinal tract consists of the esophagus, stomach, and intestines, and is divided into the upper and lower gastrointestinal tracts.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The GI tract includes all structures between the mouth and the anus, forming a continuous passageway that includes the main organs of digestion, namely, the stomach, small intestine, and large intestine.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The complete human digestive system is made up of the gastrointestinal tract plus the accessory organs of digestion (the tongue, salivary glands, pancreas, liver and gallbladder).
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The tract may also be divided into foregut, midgut, and hindgut, reflecting the embryological origin of each segment.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The whole human GI tract is about nine meters (30 feet) long at autopsy.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] It is considerably shorter in the living body because the intestines, which are tubes of smooth muscle tissue, maintain constant muscle tone in a halfway-tense state but can relax in different areas to allow for local distension and peristalsis.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The human gut microbiota is made up of around 4,000 different strains of bacteria, archaea, viruses and eukaryotes, with diverse roles in the maintenance of immune health and metabolism.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Enteroendocrine cells of the GI tract release hormones to help regulate the digestive process.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] These digestive hormones, including gastrin, secretin, cholecystokinin, and ghrelin, are mediated through either intracrine or autocrine mechanisms, indicating that the cells releasing these hormones are conserved structures throughout evolution.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The structure and function of the GI tract can be described both by gross anatomy and microscopic anatomy (histology).
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The tract itself is divided into upper and lower tracts, and the intestines into small and large intestines.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The upper gastrointestinal tract consists of the mouth, pharynx, esophagus, stomach, and duodenum.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The exact demarcation between the upper and lower tracts is the suspensory muscle of the duodenum.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] This differentiates the embryonic borders between the foregut and midgut, and is also the division commonly used by clinicians to describe gastrointestinal bleeding as being of either "upper" or "lower" origin.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Upon dissection, the duodenum may appear to be a unified organ, but it is divided into four segments based on function, location, and internal anatomy.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The four segments of the duodenum are as follows (starting at the stomach, and moving toward the jejunum): bulb, descending, horizontal, and ascending.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The suspensory muscle of the duodenum suspends the superior border of the ascending duodenum from the diaphragm, and serves as an important anatomical landmark showing the formal division between the duodenum and the jejunum, the first and second parts of the small intestine, respectively.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] This is a thin muscle which is derived from the embryonic mesoderm.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The lower gastrointestinal tract includes most of the small intestine and all of the large intestine.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] In human anatomy, the **intestine** (**bowel** or **gut**; Greek: **éntera**) is the segment of the gastrointestinal tract extending from the pyloric sphincter of the stomach to the anus and as in other mammals, consists of two segments: the small intestine and the large intestine.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] In humans, the small intestine is further subdivided into the duodenum, jejunum, and ileum.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The large intestine is subdivided into the cecum, and ascending, transverse, descending, and sigmoid colons, rectum, and anal canal.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The small intestine is a tubular structure around 6 to 7 m long, that begins at the duodenum, and ends at the ileum.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Its mucosal area in an adult human is about 30 m2 (320 sq ft).
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The combination of the circular folds, the villi, and the microvilli increases the absorptive area of the mucosa about 600-fold, making a total area of about 250 m2 (2,700 sq ft) for the entire small intestine.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Its main function is to absorb the products of digestion (including carbohydrates, proteins, lipids, and vitamins) into the bloodstream.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Jejunum: This is the midsection of the small intestine, connecting the duodenum to the ileum.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] It is about 2.5 m (8.2 ft) long and contains the circular folds also known as plicae circulares and villi that increase its surface area.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Products of digestion (sugars, amino acids, and fatty acids) are absorbed into the bloodstream here.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Ileum: The final section of the small intestine.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] It is about 3 m long, and contains villi similar to the jejunum.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] It absorbs mainly vitamin B12 and bile acids, as well as any other remaining nutrients.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The large intestine forms an arch starting at the cecum and ending at the rectum and anal canal.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] It also includes the appendix, which is attached to the cecum.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Its length is about 1.5 m, and the area of the mucosa in an adult human is about 2 m2 (22 sq ft).
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The longest part of the large intestine is the colon whose main function is to absorb water and salts.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The large intestine begins at the cecum, where the appendix is located.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] This is also the start of the colon as the ascending colon in the back wall of the abdomen.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] At the right colic flexure (hepatic flexure) (the flexed portion of the ascending and transverse colon) it runs across the abdomen in the transverse colon, passing below the diaphragm.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] At the left colic flexure (splenic flexure) the flexed portion of the transverse and descending colon, it descends down the left side of the abdomen.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] It reaches the sigmoid colon which is a loop of the colon closest to the rectum and continues to the rectum and anal canal.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The gut is an endoderm-derived structure.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] At approximately the sixteenth day of human development, the embryo begins to fold ventrally (with the embryo's ventral surface becoming concave) in two directions: the sides of the embryo fold in on each other and the head and tail fold toward one another.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The result is that a piece of the yolk sac, an endoderm-lined structure in contact with the ventral aspect of the embryo, begins to be pinched off to become the **primitive gut**.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The yolk sac remains connected to the gut tube via the vitelline duct.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Usually, this structure regresses during development; in cases where it does not, it is known as Meckel's diverticulum.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] During fetal life, the primitive gut is gradually patterned into three segments: foregut, midgut, and hindgut.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Although these terms are often used in reference to segments of the primitive gut, they are also used regularly to describe regions of the definitive gut as well.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Each segment of the gut is further specified and gives rise to specific gut and gut-related structures in later development.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Components derived from the gut proper, including the stomach and colon, develop as swellings or dilatations in the cells of the primitive gut.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] In contrast, gut-related derivatives — that is, those structures that derive from the primitive gut but are not part of the gut proper, in general, develop as out-pouchings of the primitive gut.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The blood vessels supplying these structures remain constant throughout development.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The gastrointestinal tract has a form of general histology with some differences that reflect the specialization in functional anatomy.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The mucosa is the innermost layer of the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The mucosa surrounds the lumen, or open space within the tube.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] This layer comes in direct contact with digested food (chyme).
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The mucosae are highly specialized in each organ of the gastrointestinal tract to deal with the different conditions.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The most variation is seen in the epithelium.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The submucosa consists of a layer of dense irregular connective tissue with large blood vessels, lymphatics, and nerves branching into the mucosa and muscular layer.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] It contains the submucosal plexus, an enteric nervous plexus, situated on the inner surface of the *muscularis externa*.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The muscular layer consists of an inner circular layer and a longitudinal outer layer.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The circular layer prevents food from traveling backward and the longitudinal layer shortens the tract.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The layers are not truly longitudinal or circular, rather the layers of muscle are helical with different pitches.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The inner circular is helical with a steep pitch and the outer longitudinal is helical with a much shallower pitch.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Whilst the muscularis externa is similar throughout the entire gastrointestinal tract, an exception is the stomach which has an additional inner oblique muscular layer to aid with grinding and mixing of food.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The muscularis externa of the stomach is composed of the inner oblique layer, middle circular layer, and the outer longitudinal layer.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Between the circular and longitudinal muscle layers is the myenteric plexus.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Activity is initiated by the pacemaker cells, (myenteric interstitial cells of Cajal).
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The gut has intrinsic peristaltic activity (basal electrical rhythm) due to its self-contained enteric nervous system.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The rate can be modulated by the rest of the autonomic nervous system.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The coordinated contractions of these layers is called peristalsis and propels the food through the tract.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Food in the GI tract is called a bolus (ball of food) from the mouth down to the stomach.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] After the stomach, the food is partially digested and semi-liquid, and is referred to as chyme.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] In the large intestine, the remaining semi-solid substance is referred to as feces.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The outermost layer of the gastrointestinal tract consists of several layers of connective tissue.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Intraperitoneal parts of the GI tract are covered with serosa.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] These include most of the stomach, first part of the duodenum, all of the small intestine, caecum and appendix, transverse colon, sigmoid colon and rectum.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] In these sections of the gut, there is a clear boundary between the gut and the surrounding tissue.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] These parts of the tract have a mesentery.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Retroperitoneal parts are covered with adventitia.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] They blend into the surrounding tissue and are fixed in position.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] For example, the retroperitoneal section of the duodenum usually passes through the transpyloric plane.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] These include the esophagus, pylorus of the stomach, distal duodenum, ascending colon, descending colon and anal canal.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] In addition, the oral cavity has adventitia.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Approximately 20,000 protein coding genes are expressed in human cells and 75% of these genes are expressed in at least one of the different parts of the digestive organ system.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Over 600 of these genes are more specifically expressed in one or more parts of the GI tract and the corresponding proteins have functions related to digestion of food and uptake of nutrients.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Examples of specific proteins with such functions are pepsinogen PGC and the lipase LIPF, expressed in chief cells, and gastric ATPase ATP4A and gastric intrinsic factor GIF, expressed in parietal cells of the stomach mucosa.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Specific proteins expressed in the stomach and duodenum involved in defence include mucin proteins, such as mucin 6 and intelectin-1.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The time taken for food to transit through the gastrointestinal tract varies on multiple factors, including age, ethnicity, and gender.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Several techniques have been used to measure transit time, including radiography following a barium-labeled meal, breath hydrogen analysis, scintigraphic analysis following a radiolabeled meal, and simple ingestion and spotting of corn kernels.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] It takes 2.5 to 3 hours for 50% of the contents to leave the stomach.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The rate of digestion is also dependent of the material being digested, as food composition from the same meal may leave the stomach at different rates.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Total emptying of the stomach takes around 4–5 hours, and transit through the colon takes 30 to 50 hours.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The gastrointestinal tract forms an important part of the immune system.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The surface area of the digestive tract is estimated to be about 32 square meters, or about half a badminton court.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] With such a large exposure (more than fifteen times larger than the exposed surface of the skin), critical immune components function to prevent pathogens from entering the blood and lymph circulatory systems.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Fundamental components of this protection are provided by the intestinal mucosal barrier, which is composed of physical, biochemical, and immune elements elaborated by the intestinal mucosa.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Microorganisms also are kept at bay by an extensive immune system comprising the gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT).
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] There are additional factors contributing to protection from pathogen invasion.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] For example, low pH (ranging from 1 to 4) of the stomach is fatal for many microorganisms that enter it.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Similarly, mucus (containing IgA antibodies) neutralizes many pathogenic microorganisms.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Other factors in the GI tract contributing to immune function include enzymes secreted in the saliva and bile.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Beneficial bacteria also can contribute to the homeostasis of the gastrointestinal immune system.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] For example, Clostridia, one of the most predominant bacterial groups in the GI tract, play an important role in influencing the dynamics of the gut's immune system.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] It has been demonstrated that the intake of a high fiber diet could be responsible for the induction of T-regulatory cells (Tregs).
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] This is due to the production of short-chain fatty acids during the fermentation of plant-derived nutrients such as butyrate and propionate.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Basically, the butyrate induces the differentiation of Treg cells by enhancing histone H3 acetylation in the promoter and conserved non-coding sequence regions of the FOXP3 locus, thus regulating the T cells, resulting in the reduction of the inflammatory response and allergies.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The large intestine contains multiple types of bacteria, and other microorganisms that can break down molecules the human body cannot process alone, demonstrating a symbiotic relationship.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] These microbes are responsible for gas production at host–pathogen interface, which is released as flatulence.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Intestinal bacteria can also participate in biosynthesis reactions.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] For example, certain strains in the large intestine produce vitamin B12; an essential compound in humans for things like DNA synthesis and red blood cell production.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] However, the primary function of the large intestine is water absorption from digested material (regulated by the hypothalamus) and the reabsorption of sodium and nutrients.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Beneficial intestinal bacteria compete with potentially harmful bacteria for space and nutrients, as the intestinal tract has limited resources.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] A ratio of 80–85% beneficial to 15–20% potentially harmful bacteria is proposed for maintaining homeostasis.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] An imbalanced ratio results in dysbiosis.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Enzymes such as CYP3A4, along with the antiporter activities, are also instrumental in the intestine's role of drug metabolism in the detoxification of antigens and xenobiotics.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] In most vertebrates, including amphibians, birds, reptiles, egg-laying mammals, and some fish, the gastrointestinal tract ends in a cloaca and not an anus.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] In the cloaca, the urinary system is fused with the genito-anal pore.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Therians (all mammals that do not lay eggs, including humans) possess separate anal and uro-genital openings.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] The females of the subgroup Placentalia have even separate urinary and genital openings.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] During early development, the asymmetric position of the bowels and inner organs is initiated (see also axial twist theory).
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Ruminants show many specializations for digesting and fermenting tough plant material, consisting of additional stomach compartments, and the ability to regurgitate partially digested food material for further chewing (aka "chewing cud").
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Many birds and other animals have a specialised stomach in the digestive tract called a gizzard used for grinding up food.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Another feature found in a range of animals is the crop.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] In birds this is found as a pouch alongside the esophagus.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] In 2020, the oldest known fossil digestive tract, of an extinct wormlike organism in the Cloudinidae was discovered; it lived during the late Ediacaran period about 550 million years ago.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] A stretched gut without the middle part closed is present in another branch of bilaterians, the extinct proarticulates.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] This and the amphistomic development (when both mouth and anus develop from the gut stretch in the embryo) present in some nephrozoans (e.g. roundworms) are considered to support this hypothesis.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] There are many diseases and conditions that can affect the gastrointestinal system, including infections, inflammation and cancer.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Various pathogens, such as bacteria that cause foodborne illnesses, can induce gastroenteritis which results from inflammation of the stomach and small intestine.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Antibiotics to treat such bacterial infections can decrease the microbiome diversity of the gastrointestinal tract, and further enable inflammatory mediators.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Gastroenteritis is the most common disease of the GI tract.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Diverticular disease is a condition that is very common in older people in industrialized countries.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] It usually affects the large intestine but has been known to affect the small intestine as well.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Diverticulosis occurs when pouches form on the intestinal wall.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Once the pouches become inflamed it is known as diverticulitis.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Inflammatory bowel disease is an inflammatory condition affecting the bowel walls, and includes the subtypes Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] While Crohn's can affect the entire gastrointestinal tract, ulcerative colitis is limited to the large intestine.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Crohn's disease is widely regarded as an autoimmune disease.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Although ulcerative colitis is often treated as though it were an autoimmune disease, there is no consensus that it actually is such.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Functional gastrointestinal disorders the most common of which is irritable bowel syndrome.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Functional constipation and chronic functional abdominal pain are other functional disorders of the intestine that have physiological causes but do not have identifiable structural, chemical, or infectious pathologies.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Gastrointestinal surgery can often be performed in the outpatient setting.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] In the United States in 2012, operations on the digestive system accounted for 3 of the 25 most common ambulatory surgery procedures and constituted 9.1 percent of all outpatient ambulatory surgeries.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Intestines from animals other than humans are used in a number of ways.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] From each species of livestock that is a source of milk, a corresponding rennet is obtained from the intestines of milk-fed calves.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Pig and calf intestines are eaten, and pig intestines are used as sausage casings.
[src:acanthocephala/alimentary-canal] Calf intestines supply calf-intestinal alkaline phosphatase (CIP), and are used to make goldbeater's skin.
